    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-06-19T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-06-19T07:00:00-05:00" n="496"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d496">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">357.<gloss target="#t_AC1">AC</gloss>/6–1950:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Syria</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Keeley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Damascus</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-06-19T14:00:00+02:00"
                            >June 19, 1950—2 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>347. <gloss target="#t_reDepcirtel1">ReDepcirtel</gloss> June 16, 6 a.m.<note
                        n="1" xml:id="d496fn1">Not printed; but see footnote 1 to telegram 730 from
                        Geneva, <ref target="#pg_931">p. 931</ref>.</note> Legation has repeatedly
                    pointed out that more conciliatory attitude on part of Israel re <gloss
                        target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> resolutions on refugees and boundaries would seem
                    prerequisite to any <pb facs="0956" n="934" xml:id="pg_934"/> expectation of
                    negotiations by Arab League States with Israel (<gloss target="#t_Legdes1"
                        >Legdes</gloss> 352 June 16, 314 June 5, 224 April 18, etc.). Legation
                    believes that impasse can be bridged only if right at least to repatriation of
                    Palestine Arabs and our compensation of those resettled elsewhere accepted in
                    principle, by Israel. If Israel agrees in principle to negotiate on basis
                    pertinent <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> Resolutions, it should be possible
                    to find a formula for final settlement based on realities situation through give
                    and-take of actual negotiations.</p>
                <p>In comment on forthcoming tripartite statement, Legation suggested that endeavor
                    to remove in text any possibility implication acceptance territorial <hi
                        rend="italic">statics quo</hi> should be made (<gloss target="#t_Legtel1"
                        >Legtel</gloss> 256 May 7). Separate French <hi rend="italic">démarche</hi>
                    requesting assurances from Syria and Lebanon prior to joint delivery of note,
                    interpreted locally as sphere of influence deal, was unforeseen development.
                    These two aspects statement were largely seized upon by unfriendly local press
                    to discredit good faith of agreement as whole. Legation is still of opinion that
                    tripartite statement was welcome in Syria by more responsible political (<gloss
                        target="#t_Legtel1">Legtel</gloss> 299 May 28) and military (<gloss
                        target="#t_Legtel1">Legtel</gloss> 315 June 2) circles notwithstanding press
                    campaign to discredit it.</p>
                <p>Sent Department 347; repeated info unnumbered Arab capitals, Tel Aviv, Jerusalem,
                    London, Paris, Ankara.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Keeley</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
